I have generated `candidate.py` based on an **evidence-scaled multidimensional prototype heuristic**. 

Following the brief to explore a higher-variance/simpler alternative to the Bayesian model, this model operates on three distinct heuristic deviations from a random "prototype":
1. Imbalance of heads vs tails (`imbalance`)
2. Deviation from an ideal alternation rate (`abs(p_alts - theta_alt)`)
3. Length of the longest run (`max_run_norm`)

A critical flaw with previous prototype heuristics was that they did not account for the sequence length (i.e. longer sequences are evaluated as more confidently un-random than shorter ones with the exact same proportions). This model adds a flexible `length_power` scaling parameter that scales the total penalty by a function of the sequence length (`pt.pow(n, length_power)`).

